title: For Sale/Trade:  WINCHESTER MODEL 70 SUPER GRADE AFRICAN 458 WIN MAG ONE OWNER
postcontent:
My uncle ordered this rifle from the Winchester Custom Shop in January of 64 and purchased it from Builders Hardware here in Charlotte. It was special ordered from the custom shop with the following upgrades.
Grade 3 wood instead of the grade 2 which was standard on super grades.
Winchester custom shop island express safari sights.
Kickeez recoil pad.
The wood has awesome figure and color through out the stock. The stock has very minor handling marks and the bluing is mint condition other than a tiny rub on the floor plate. I know for a fact the rifle has been fired less than 50 times since new. The rifling looks like brand new as well as the bore itself. Comes with the original dealer hanging tag as well as instruction manual. Also comes with a Browning model 1915 hand fitted safari case that was purchased fro the same place in the early 70s along with a hand tooled Torel Cape Buffalo sling. The case is in mint condition with both keys as well as the Browning instruction manual and care card. I have seen some of these on the web for sale but never one like this in mint condition as well as both keys and paper work. Last is on box of vintage Winchester Western 458 rounds and one box of empty cases. This rifle is in amazing condition to have been made in 1964. I don't think you could ever find another 64 Super Grade African 458 in this condition. Thanks very much for looking and feel free to email with any questions.

RARE Colt M1911 A1 national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in February of 1943. It was Issued to an enlisted serviceman at the time. (Trying to find out who it was issued to now through different channels.) There are specific clues on the gun that tell you who it MIGHT have gone to.. There is AA inscribed (Not stamped) on the frame Next to GHD. GHD is significant because Col. Guy H. Drewry inspected ordnance from June 17, 1942 to July 15, 1945 For COLT.

After having multiple collectors and Colt dealers at the gun show look at it. "AA" is believed to stand for "All American" 82nd Airborne. Which would match the dates the gun was issued, and the eagle carved on the Ivory grips. 82 Airborne was the first Airborne division in US Army history and had three major drops, made their first drop in July of 1943 to invade Sicily. Second was Salerno on 13 September 1943. The third was the invasion of Normandy Jun 1944.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by a gunsmith. At some point it was re-blued, and fixtures were 24k gold plated. It has been determined the gold was added many many years ago as some has worn off in spots. Bluing and finish is still very nice... Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. I have put 100 rounds through it and drives tacks. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns. email or text 918-four02-zero854.

title: For Sale/Trade:   1943 Remington Rand M1911 A1 (Original)
postcontent:
This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1943 Remington-Rand M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (Only a few blood spots) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in April of 1943. It is stamped with "FJA" inspector's mark. FJA are the initials of Frank J. Atwood, inspector of ordnance. The "P" proof mark is located near the magazine release and on top of the slide, in front of the rear sight. Cross cannons ordnance mark on the right rear of the frame, to the right of the hammer pin. "UNITED STATES PROPERTY" over the serial number with "M1911A1 U.S. ARMY" to the right of the slide stop pin. Also has the G marking on top of the frame next to the disconnector and P proof mark on top of the slide, in front of the rear sight. HS marked barrel. HS is the marking of High Standard.

This gun is all original, and a wartime piece, as you can tell by the blood spots on the slide and grip. It also comes with original U.S. marked Military issued Holster. postcontent: Our # LG981TRG This shotgun is NOT C&R eligible. Here is an excellent Chinese copy, and in some respects an improvement on, the workhorse Remington 870. Since the 870 was introduced in 1950, its patent probably expired in 2000, hence these excellent tributes to the Wingmaster. Manufacturer is Zonghzou Machine Works, Jin An China, one of the former Norinco operatives. Importer is Interstate Arms in Billerica, Massachusetts. Finish is entirely matte black with classic corncob 870P type forends in black synthetic, and matching buttstock with a nice thick recoil pad. Sight system is conventional bead sight but also with frame mounted Tactical Picatinny Rail that accepts any Weaver Style Optical mounts or device. Weight empty is about 7 1/2 pounds. Note the mar on the finish. It's a safe assumption that none of the 981 Hawks will be cosmetically perfect. Credit finish mars to the rice paper boxes that these come in, even though Chinese boxmanship has improved over the last decade. Nevertheless these are solid, quality shotguns and attractive finishwise. All of them are brand new in their original boxes, and we take great pains with rice-boxed guns when we ship them. Note the high visibility orange follower. Barrel is 18 inch Cylinder Bore, .718-.720 at the muzzle. Magazine capacity is five plus one round of 12 gauge 2 3/4 inch shells, or four plus one round of 3 inch magnum. Note the extended section of the magazine forward of the barrel lug. We have added an FM brand, Brand New Electronic Green or Red Dot Sight, adjustable two colors with brand new mounts, all excellent quality and all manufactured in the same neighborhood as the shotgun itself. All the owner will need to do is put the rings on the sight, screw it down to the rail, and zero it in. We have also added a polymer heat shield, similar to the famed Trench Guns of World War One. A Remington 870 tricked out like this one commands prices in the $700 - $800 vicinity. We're offering these excellent 870 clone shotguns, however, complete with shield, mounts and sight, each for only $ 219.00Shipping. $20 flat fee lower 48 states; $60 Alaska, Hawaii or Puerto Rico, UPS Ground with full insurance coverage. postcontent: I have decided to sell my HK MR556A1 with Aimpoint PRO. This rifle has a BD date code. For those that don't know, the HK MR556 is a short stroke piston operated rifle built as a civilian version of the 416. The 416 is in use by Marines (IAR27) and by select special forces. It is an outstandingly clean operating system. It also has been upgraded with HK licensed Troy Micro flip-up front and rear sights($190). The sights give absolute 1-1 co-witness to the Aimpoint. It has had the barrel re-profiled to the SOCOM profile by Jayson at IGF. He re-profiles and works on HK's for a living. His work is second to none. It also comes with a 14.5" SS barrel custom made to fit the HK MR556 and 416, it has been Duracoated and includes a BCM flash hider with pin to lengthen it to 16" overall. I bought the barrel for another upper but decided to let it go. The upper has a zero round count, while the lower has a 30 rounds or less count. I used it with my other upper to test the other uppers accuracy. I have a larger trigger guard on it but includes stock flat trigger guard. It has 7 HK High Reliability Magazines (2 I bought used and 5 never fired). It also has 5 HK polymer magazines. It comes with all the paperwork, HK Tool, and hard case from HK. I will include the Vickers Padded Combat two point sling with quick release. I also put rubber Magpul rail ladders on the sides and bottom of the forearm rail. The Aimpoint PRO is used but in perfect condition with box,spacer (not used as to give co-witness to the HK low profile sights), and paperwork. There is almost $500 worth of magazines at HK's price. The total of the barrel re-profile and nitriding (meloniting) is $340. The extra barrel (new), I put a value of $300 even though it cost more than that to have it made and include an extra barrel nut (not pictured). I also have an HK barrel nut tool that will fit HK's proprietary barrel nut. On a side note the barrel tab was removed by Jayson to allow either the MR556 or 416 BCGs to fit the upper, the 14.5" barrel was made without the tab, so it will work with either also. I honestly am not looking to trade for anything. Please note that I will drive within a reasonable area to meet, but prefer to deal FTF. Must show ID, CCW or PPP to buy this. Sorry for the inconvenience, but better safe than sorry. Price is firm and not negotiable. title: For Sale:  WASR-22 AK, M1 Carbine, and Type 99 Arisaka for sale
postcontent:
First is a Romanian WASR-22 chambered in .22lr. It is a full scale AKM training rifle and very similar to the real deal. However the bolt rails, front trunnion, barrel, magazine and bolt are completely different which makes it legal to own in CT, other than it being a rimfire rifle. Other than that they are the same. It accepts standard AKM stocks, grips, gas tubes, and handguards. That being said, I swapped the factory wood out for some very nice Romanian laminate. Very hard to find Romanian laminate this nice. The rifle comes with a single 10rd magazine as seen in the pictures. These rifles are very rare and unique. I am asking $600.00 cash for this. No trades please.

Second I have a very early Plainfield Machine Co. M1 Carbine. For those of you who don't know, Plainfield manufactured high quality commercial grade M1s for civilians, corrections officers, and LE. They were also known to use quite a few USGI parts on their rifles as well. This is one of their earlier models from the early 60s and therefore had pre-ban status. It comes with no magazine as I do not have any CT compliant mags for this available. I am asking $700.00 cash. Again, no trades please.

Third, I have a Type 99 Arisaka. This is from the Nagoya Arsenal and isn't a 7th series rifle. This is relatively rare as far as Arisakas go and is not a "last ditch" rifle. It is complete with top handguard and aircraft sights. The stock is uncut, but could use a refinishing. The rifle was recently in poor shape so I had it reblued. The bore is bright and shinny. I am asking $150.00 cash and only would be interested in a trade for a nice shape 91/30.

title: For Sale/Trade:  1942 Colt M1911 A1 National Match
postcontent:
RARE 1942 Colt M1911 A1 national match pistol. This is what I know about the gun. Its an original 1942 Colt M 1911 A1 US Army Issue. (matching numbers except slide does not show serial number behind hammer) According to the serial number this gun was shipped in May of 1942. It is stamped with WB inside a Box for Colonel Waldemar S. Broberg, Hartford/Springfield Ordnance District, Army Inspector of Ordnance: July 1, 1941 - June 16, 1942. The WB inspected pistols are a little more rare for that time frame.

Not sure how this gun made it back to the states, but it appears the gun was made into a national match pistol during the 1950's or early 1960's, it does not have "NM" stamped on the slide.. But not all pistols back then were stamped with "NM" for national match. There are two types of Camp Perry National Match pistols.. The kind sent back to Armories and stamped SA for Springfield Armory and NM for Colt Armory. These were tuned, and fitted by the armory for military camp perry match shooting. The second was private gunsmiths these were done in competition with the armories for the same reason. Many prominent Gunsmiths of the time wanted national match recognition and made their own finally tuned pistols. It appears this one might have been done by the military, as the barrel has been re-stamped. This gun is in its original time frame finish (parkerized). All Proof markings to fit era. Bore is excellent and looks shinning.

This pistol is a shooter. It is amazingly tight and special fitted for accuracy. Its an amazing piece of history and looks beautiful as well. Definitely a one of a kind 1911. Would be a prize piece for any collection.

I have many pictures if you want more. FTF in tulsa area only.. All reasonable offers considered. Email if interested. Will trade multiple guns.. Please list your offer and values of guns. email or text 918-four02-zero854.

title: For Sale:  Star Firestar M43 9mm Compact 1911 Style Steel Handgun. OEM Box & 2 mags, Galco Leather Holster, Ammo
postcontent:
Not abused, runs without complaint, blue is looking not too shabby, please take a look.
 It's design is sturdy, accurate, and reliable, as I'll explain further down.
I'm just looking at other things at the moment, so I'm parting with this steal of a concealed carry package.

More pictures: http://postimg.org/gallery/2g56cljv0/

Before I dive in, if you're not familiar with this brand (like I was), you can dig around the web to find that they are a Reputable manufacturer from Spain.
Their .45 caliber pistols are highly praised (The two 1911's carried by Samuel Jackson and John Travolta in Pulp Fiction are actually Star 1911 Clones), and the other bored models are made to the same standard.




This is the M43 Compact pistol, available in 9mm/.40SW/.45.
Mine is the single stack 9mm, 7 rounds +1, included is a spare mag.
It's an "all steel" gun, with an inside the frame slide, this combo makes it an accurate little automatic. The heft absorbs recoil, and from what I've read, will stand up to 9mm + P ammo. 
>>Very quick repeated shots with this overall setup, the grip, slide/body, and trigger.
The LOCKUP is tight, and the BORE is in good shape:
The RIFLING edges are pronounced, has a shine to it still, I don't think it has been used extensively.

It's single action only and can be carried in either:
CONDITION 1 (round in the chamber with the hammer cocked and the safety on), 
OR
 with a round cambered and the hammer released to a half cock. When the hammer is down, the safety will lock the slide in place.

The TRIGGER is in a nice middle ground between the very stiff and very light.
On one hand it is just at the point that it takes a deliberate finger pull to fire,
 and on the other hand: the trigger reset is short and it has an almost two-stage feel.
 When pulled back, it comes to a tangible rest just before the break.
>>Very quick repeated shots with this overall setup, the grip, slide/body, and trigger.

AMBIDEXTROUS SAFETY, just like on a 1911. The beaver tail grip and indent under the trigger guard give you a surprisingly solid GRIP on the gun. If you have *big* hands, you'll probably dangle a pinky.



Included is the original Star FireStar CARRYING CASE,
 a SPARE MAGAZINE stainless 7 round,
 a Galco Leather Inside the Waistband IWB Locking HOLSTER,
 and ONE BOX of econo-target range AMMO I have leftover.

I have found a great web page for this gun, and have a PDF copy of the original MANUAL, I'll have that printed out for you.

This gun needs to be kept clean and lubricated to work properly, and it prefers quality ammo due to it's stiff recoil spring. The hotter, the better.




I'm asking $310 for the lot, I can meet anywhere public, I'd prefer to meet at a Police station (they won't be involved in the sale, however they don't mind for our safety).
Bill of sale with documentation of the Serial #, our DL #'s and FOID card if applicable.

If you wish to send a message, please email me.
I can be reached by phone at 2One 97 Nin e87Sev en 4 8,
-Tom

postcontent:
Adams Arm Gas Piston Complete upper
The 5.56 Carbine Quad Rail 16" Upper is a standard M4 style upper that incorporates the patented Adams Arms technology. The piston system parts and the barrel have been treated with our salt nitride Meloniting process making them harder and more corrosive resistant than hard chrome. Add the patented Adams Arms piston system and you'll have an upper that will run cleaner, cooler, and longer than any other AR upper you own.

Barrel Material: Voodoo Chrome Moly Vanadium Steel
finished with our proprietary QPQ Melonite process inside and out. Unlike hard chrome and magnesium phosphate, Melonite is a molecular bonding process with the metal. It allows the chemicals to seep down below the surface area of the metal, instead of just adding a top layer. This means that the barrel can be cut to a true rifle bore while maintaining complete corrosion resistance and virtually no wear. It also means that the protection offered is not just a thin layer on top of the material but actually penetrates layers deep ensuring that it does not wear off. Now you have the velocities of a stainless steel true rifle bore with complete protection! You can out last a chrome lined barrel and shoot with the accuracy and efficiency of a stainless steel barrel, all without breaking the bank

title: For Sale:  LaRue Tactical SPR/M4 Scope Mount QD LT104
postcontent:
SKU: LT104-30-VFZ
Ring Size: 30mm
Mounting Type: VFZ Mount

I apologize for the upside-down pictures. Armslists appears to always have a problem with my pictures.

One lightly used LaRue SPR/M4 Scope Mount. Skip the postage and wait; buy it here from me! I'm selling it because I sold my 30mm scope, and instead of buying another 30mm, I ended up getting a 35mm. $150 OBO. 


From LaRue Website:

The Industry Standard.
The LT104 is the best mount made for attaching high-power riflescopes onto flattop-style AR15's, period.

The LT104 places the centerline of the optic 1.5" above the top of the rail for optimum cheek weld with a variety of AR-platform rifles. The cantilever positions the scope out front over the handguard, eliminating the need to span from the receiver to the handguard. The cantilever also allows the shooter to obtain proper eye relief.

The popularity of the SPR series of mounts is partially due to the innovative backbone that connects the split vertical rings. This design provides a more robust platform for the optics, increases repeatability, and eliminates the need for time-consuming lapping. The rings are precision-machined with the tightest tolerances, and feature threaded steel inserts, built to withstand a lifetime of abuse.

Like all LaRue mounts, it is precision-machined out of bar-stock aluminum and anodized. The locking LaRue Speed Levers provide outstanding return to zero; the optic can be removed, and replaced, without loss of zero. Guaranteed.

Assembly and adjustment only takes a few minutes, then off to the range.

About VFZ Mounts:
VFZ is a new theory in the concept of clamping accessories to MIL-STD-1913 rails. Instead of using a horizontal cross-bolt, the VFZ uses a vertical bolt that draws up a clamping foot against the lower angle of the rail, seating the mount similarly to a fully-closed LaRue lever.

Once installed on the firearm, index marks allow the user to remove the mount, then reattach to the same tension, providing unprecedented return to zero for a non-QD-levered mount. The unique vertical alignment of the clamp allows components that are structurally stronger than traditional cross-bolt designs.
